Which statistical test is suitable?

Reference: A Choosing models and tests | APS 240: Data Analysis and Statistics with R (dzchilds.github.io)

Step 2 Statistical analysis

1. Install R packages for T-test calculation on each rows

install.packages('matrixTests',dependencies=TRUE)
library(matrixTests)

2. Perform Welchs T-test (Independent T-test) on (log-transformed) normalized data

#row_t_welch(columns for treatment group, columns for control group)
hcchealthyttest<-row_t_welch(hcc_healthy_log[,grepl("HCC", names(hcc_healthy_log))] , hcc_healthy_log[,grepl("Healthy", names(hcc_healthy_log))], alternative = "two.sided")

3. Multiple test correction

Rationale:

Methods:

#p.adjust(column that contains P value,"which correction method")
hcchealthyttest$FDR <- p.adjust(hcchealthyttest$pvalue, "BH")

4. Calculate Fold Change (FC)

#create new column (FC) 
hcchealthyttest$FC <- 2^(hcchealthyttest$mean.x-hcchealthyttest$mean.y)

5. Convert FC<1 to negative values (Downregulated genes)

#convert those FC with values smaller than 1 to negative fold change
#for better interpretation/comparison with those FC values>1
#create new column (finalfc)
#ifelse(if this condition, then do this, if not do this instead)
hcchealthyttest$finalfc <- ifelse(hcchealthyttest$FC <1, -1/hcchealthyttest$FC,hcchealthyttest$FC)

Exercise 1

  1. a. Identify genes that pass FDR<=0.05 and |FC|>=1.5. Name the new dataset as fdr005fc1.5

    b. Repeat step a and b by changing the criteria to

    1. FDR<=0.05 and |FC|>=2, Name the new dataset as fdr005fc2

    2. P value<=0.05 and |FC|>=1.5, Name the new dataset as p005fc1.5

    3. P value<=0.05 and |FC|>=2, Name the new dataset as p005fc2

    d. Summarize how many genes that pass the criteria =

FDR or P value <=0.05 FC criteria Number of genes that passed both criteria
FDR<=0.05 |FC|>=1.5 ?
FDR<=0.05 |FC|>=2 ?
P<=0.05 |FC|>=1.5 ?
P<=0.05 |FC|>=2 ? 

#filter according to FDR and FC
fdr005fc1.5<-filter(hcchealthyttest,FDR<=0.05 & abs(finalfc)>=1.5)
#429

fdr005fc2<-filter(hcchealthyttest,FDR<=0.05 & abs(finalfc)>=2)
#85

p005fc1.5<-filter(hcchealthyttest,pvalue<=0.05 & abs(finalfc)>=1.5)
#497

p005fc2<-filter(hcchealthyttest,pvalue<=0.05 & abs(finalfc)>=2)
#85

Step 3b Data visualization

i) Heatmap - Visualize all significantly differentially expressed lncRNAs/mRNAs between all HCC and healthy samples

1. Install R packages for heatmap

install.packages("gplots")

2. Load the packages

library(gplots)

3. Obtain expression data for differentially expressed RNAs

library(dplyr)
#filter(which dataset(rownames of this dataset)%in% (also appear in rownames of another dataset))
#need to change the dataset name (sigbyfdr)
sigrnaexp<-filter(hcc_healthy_log,rownames(hcc_healthy_log) %in% rownames(fdr005fc1.5))

Reference: https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/data-wrangling-cheatsheet.pdf

4. Convert data frame to matrix for heatmap

#as.matrix(data frame name)
sigrnaexp_mat<-as.matrix(sigrnaexp)

5. Specify two groups that you wish to compare and colours for each group

#in order to specify hcc and healthy group as a new variable, we keep only the first 3 characters of column names
#substr(column name of the dataset,start from which element, stop at which element)
#convert the characters as factor
my_group<-as.factor(substr(colnames(sigrnaexp),1,3))

6. Install package for colour palettes

install.packages("RcolorBrewer")

7. Load the package

library(RColorBrewer)

8. View the available colour palettes

display.brewer.all()

9. Specify colours for the groups (on top of heatmap)

#specify colours that you want for the two groups
colSide<-brewer.pal(9,"Set1")[my_group]

10. Specify colours for gene expression on heatmap (red : upregulated; green: downregulated; black: low expression)

colgradient<-colorRampPalette(c("green","black","red"))(10)

11. Draw heatmap

heatmap.2(sigrnaexp_mat,col=colgradient,scale="row",trace="none",ColSideColors = colSide, density.info="none")

12. Add Figure legend

legend(x="left",legend=c("HCC","Healthy"),fill=brewer.pal(9,"Set1"))
Save the image

ii) Volcano plot - Visualize significantly differentially expressed lncRNAs/mRNAs in HCC patients vs Healthy individuals

#create a new column called gene_symbol
hcchealthyttest$gene_symbol<-row.names(hcchealthyttest)

#create another new column called diffexpressed
hcchealthyttest$diffexpressed <- "NO"
# if log2Foldchange > 1.5 and FDR < 0.05, set as "UP" 
hcchealthyttest$diffexpressed[hcchealthyttest$finalfc > 1.5 & hcchealthyttest$FDR < 0.05] <- "UP"
# if log2Foldchange < -1.5 and FDR < 0.05, set as "DOWN"
hcchealthyttest$diffexpressed[hcchealthyttest$finalfc < -1.5 & hcchealthyttest$FDR < 0.05] <- "DOWN"

#create a new column called delabel - to label those not differentially expressed as No
hcchealthyttest$delabel <- NA
hcchealthyttest$delabel[hcchealthyttest$diffexpressed != "NO"] <- hcchealthyttest$gene_symbol[hcchealthyttest$diffexpressed != "NO"]

#simple volcano plot
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data=hcchealthyttest, aes(x=finalfc, y=-log10(FDR), col=diffexpressed, label=delabel)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_text()
  1. Install a new package to organize the labels
install.packages("ggrepel")
  1. Load the package and draw volcano plot
# load library
library(ggrepel)
# plot adding up all layers we have seen so far
ggplot(data=hcchealthyttest, aes(x=finalfc, y=-log10(FDR), col=diffexpressed, label=delabel)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_text_repel() +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("blue", "black", "red")) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=c(-0.6, 0.6), col="red") +
  geom_hline(yintercept=-log10(0.05), col="red")

iii) Boxplot - Visualize individual differentially expressed lncRNAs/mRNAs in HCC patients vs Healthy individuals

In this example, we will draw boxplot on the most upregulated gene

1. Install R packages for boxplots

install.packages("ggplot2")

2. Load the package

library(ggplot2)

3. Sort the FC and FDR or find the max values of FC

#to sort based on a column in ascending order
#order(dataframe$column names)

#sort in descending order
#order(-dataframe$column names)

#sort based on multiple columns
#order(dataframe$column 1 name, dataframe$column 2 name)
sigrnaexp_sorted<-sigrnaexp[order(-fdr005fc1.5$finalfc,fdr005fc1.5$FDR),]

4. Convert the data into long format (contains value in only one column)

Example of data in wide format and long format :

Reference: https://www.r-bloggers.com/2016/09/reshape-r-package-reshape2-melt-and-cast/

#install package that reshape data and install
install.packages("reshape")
library(reshape)
#melt the first row (that contains the most upregulated gene) into long format
#melt(dataframe)
rna1<-melt((sigrnaexp_sorted[1,]))

Exercise 2

5. Convert HCC and healthy sample IDs to just HCC or Healthy label

In this example, we create a new column (Column name is Sampletypes)

eg. recode HCC001, HCC002etc to HCC in Sampletypes column while Healthy001,Healthy002etc to Healthy in Sampletypes column

rna1_rename<-rna1%>%mutate(Sampletypes=case_when(grepl("HCC",rna1$variable)~"HCC",grepl("Healthy",rna1$variable)~"Healthy"))

6. Draw boxplot using ggplot function

Hint: use geom_boxplot()

ggplot(rna1_rename,aes(x=Sampletypes,y=value))+geom_boxplot()
